<HEADLINE>
<P>
BOYS' BASKETBALL ROUNDUP; TON LEADS GRIFFINS BY DORSEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL ITAGAKI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Los Alamitos point guard Ali Ton and his teammates made a statement in a 60-47 
victory over Los Angeles Dorsey in the first round of the Tournament of 
Champions boys' basketball tournament Tuesday night at Ocean View High. 
</P>
<P>
 Ton had 17 points, 11 assists and six steals to help the Griffins (6-1) break 
open a close game by outscoring Dorsey, 21-9, in the fourth quarter.Los 
Alamitos plays the winner of the Tustin-Pasadena game in Thursday's 
quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
 "That's the best we've played all season," Los Alamitos Coach Steve Brooks 
said. "I have all the confidence in the world in Ali. I think he's the best 
set-up point guard in the area. He took control of the game." 
</P>
<P>
 Ton did most of his set-up work for 6-foot-7 center Jeremy Vandervoet and Cory 
Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
 Vandervoet finished with 17 points. He benefited from numerous assists when 
Ton drove down the lane and dished off to his center for layups. 
</P>
<P>
 When Dorsey tried to pressure the Griffins, Ton and guard Chris Glass knifed 
through the press in the fourth quarter and Johnson made the Dons pay. 
</P>
<P>
 Johnson made four three-pointers in the final quarter, finishing with 17 
points, to help put away the game. 
</P>
<P>
 "I was pleased with the effort tonight," Brooks said. "But it's just one 
game." 
</P>
<P>
 Los Alamitos has lost only one game this season -- a 56-39 defeat Dec. 7 
against Mater Dei, the No. 1-ranked team in the state. 
</P>
<P>
 Dorsey (1-1), ranked in the state preseason top 20, was led by Charles 
Johnson's 13 points and six rebounds. MICHAEL ITAGAKI 
</P>
