<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY ALMANAC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Trees and computers: they go together in Irvine. The Public Works Department 
keeps a detailed computer record of each of the city's 38,000 trees, including 
when each tree was last trimmed. 
</P>
<P>
 During fiscal 1994-95, the city will trim 4,658 trees in the villages of 
University Park, Turtle Rock, California Homes and the Ranch. Some 1,446 
eucalyptus trees, planted to form windrows in the city, will also be trimmed in 
the villages of El Camino Real and Woodbridge. 
</P>
<P>
 As the number of trees increases in the 23-year-old city, tree counters in the 
Public Works Department have found it cumbersome to keep track of them on the 
city's mainframe computer. They're currently downloading all tree records into 
a PC-based system. Today 
</P>
<P>
 The Orange Coast College Wind Ensemble and Concert Choir will perform holiday 
and classical favorites at 6:30 p.m. in the Rotated Square at John Wayne 
Airport. The square is on the airport's upper level in front of the Orange 
Grill restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
 Admission is free to this third annual concert. 
</P>
<P>
 The wind ensemble is directed by Dana Wheaton, and the choir is directed by 
Charlie Clark. 
</P>
<P>
 Additional information on the concert or on joining the musical groups is 
available by calling (714) 432-5985. 
</P>
</TEXT>
