<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: SADDLEBACK / SOUTH BEACH; SAN JUAN CAPISTRANO; COUNCIL 
OKS REVISED CITY WORKER CONTRACTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF BEAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council has approved contracts that trim some health benefits for two 
city employee unions to allow for pay raises for some employees. 
</P>
<P>
 The council last week approved the agreements with the San Juan Capistrano 
Management Employees Assn. and the San Juan Capistrano City Employees Assn.The 
two unions represent more than 70 employees and include every city worker 
except department heads. 
</P>
<P>
 The agreements were based on a compensation study done for the city. The study 
found that 19 of the city's union employees made more than comparable employees 
in the private and public sectors. 
</P>
<P>
 Those employees' salaries will be frozen this year, said Cynthia Pendleton, 
director of administrative services. 
</P>
<P>
 Pendleton said that the contracts will expire June 30, 1995, and that salary 
increases will be retroactive to Nov. 1. 
</P>
<P>
 The health benefits savings to pay for the salary increases will be about 
$100,000, Pendleton said. JEFF BEAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
