<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAGUNA MAN ARRESTED IN UNLICENSED INSURANCE FIRM CASE; CRIME: THE COMPANY SOLD 
WORTHLESS AUTO POLICIES, WITH PREMIUMS TOTALING $11.2 MILLION, AUTHORITIES SAY. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KEN ELLINGWOOD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Authorities have arrested the former owner of a Laguna Beach insurance firm 
accused of selling 15,000 worthless auto insurance policies, state officials 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 Robert M. Granafei, 46, of Laguna Beach surrendered to authorities Monday on 
suspicion of running an unlicensed insurance company, which officials said left 
nearly 500 claims unpaid, according to state Insurance Commissioner John 
Garamendi. 
</P>
<P>
 Granafei, released on $10,000 bail, is to be arraigned Jan. 9 on a felony 
count and three misdemeanor charges of illegal operation. 
</P>
<P>
 The state Department of Insurance shut down the Underwriters Reserve Ltd. in 
May, 1993, on suspicion that it had sold worthless auto policies costing a 
yearly average of $750. The department also seized affiliates in Fountain 
Valley, Downey and Lakeside. Insurance Department spokeswoman Candysse Miller 
said it and the Orange County district attorney's office have been 
investigating the case in the year and a half since then.  
</P>
<P>
 "They've been looking at the case since that time, tracking money and also 
sorting out the business," she said. Granafei faces a maximum of three years in 
jail if he is found guilty. The law doesn't require him to pay the money back, 
but Miller said investigators are trying to find ways to have policyholders 
reimbursed as much as possible. 
</P>
<P>
 The company operated for nearly a year, collecting $11.2 million in premiums, 
Garamendi said. Authorities have seized nearly $2 million in assets, most of 
which were in a Swiss bank account, Garamendi said. 
</P>
<P>
 Garamendi said the company violated state law barring unlicensed California 
firms from selling insurance. The company claimed to be based in the Caribbean 
island of St. Kitts, but investigators found it was run from Laguna Beach, 
Garamendi said. 
</P>
<P>
 He said unpaid claims from 472 policyholders total $4.8 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
