<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; WASHINGTON, D.C.; NEW SYSTEM TO BEAM WIDE-RANGING ALERTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Federal agencies unveiled a new Emergency Alert System designed to warn the 
public of everything from wars to hurricanes by beaming information to their 
television sets, radios, pagers and compact disc players. The new system can 
activate consumer electronic devices even when they are turned off. It is the 
successor of the old Emergency Broadcast System, whose repetitive tests on 
broadcast channels have long been tuned out by most people as boring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
