<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; MICHIGAN; ASSISTED SUICIDE BAN HELD CONSTITUTIONAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 There is no constitutional right to assisted suicide, and Michigan's ban on 
the practice is constitutional, the state Supreme Court ruled.The ruling in 
Lansing came on four combined cases, three of them involving criminal charges 
against Dr. Jack Kevorkian, who has been present at 21 deaths since 1990. The 
fourth was a civil challenge on behalf of two cancer patients and some medical 
professionals. The court said assisted suicide has been a crime under common 
law and someone could be prosecuted for that even without the Legislature 
enacting its temporary ban in 1993. 
